messages.content:
 I was thinking about visual tokenisation for language model's compatible images representation.
    • split input image into chunks; 
    • for each chunk generate visual embedding vector (including positional relationship and contextualised information);
(during training phase) 
    • save encountered embeddings for all chunks of all images in dataset; 
    • use k-means to group similar vectors; 
    • for each K save pair id and weighed average of vector embeddings in clusters;
(during visual tokenizer downstream use) 
    • tokenizer receive input image, split into chunks, embed patches and finds closest in it's dictionary; 
    • tokenizer output is a linearized visual tokens sequence with line separator (to get 1d from 2d matrix of chunks);
This representation is used for downstream tasks, including language modelling with mixture of text with visual information. Of course, we can add more vectorized representation (in addition to previously described, which works with pixel grid) - let's say, we have an image and we want to represent it using graphical primitives (lines, curves, shapes, strokes, dots, etc) with parameters (position, rotation, scale by Oxy, z-index and, probably, colour scheme) optimized to minimize error between source image and reconstructed (rasterized) from representation.
May I ask for analytical decomposition of proposed approach?
